======================================================================
6. KEY INSIGHT: SLOPE GROWTH IMPLIES AMPLIFIED ADVANTAGE
======================================================================
  p=  7, m=  3: b_3=     1, b_5=       0, b_7=         0, b_5/b_3=     0.0, b_7/b_5=    0.00
  p= 11, m=  5: b_3=     1, b_5=       3, b_7=         0, b_5/b_3=     3.0, b_7/b_5=    0.00
  p= 13, m=  6: b_3=     1, b_5=       6, b_7=         1, b_5/b_3=     6.0, b_7/b_5=    0.17
  p= 17, m=  8: b_3=     1, b_5=      15, b_7=        15, b_5/b_3=    15.0, b_7/b_5=    1.00
  p= 19, m=  9: b_3=     1, b_5=      21, b_7=        35, b_5/b_3=    21.0, b_7/b_5=    1.67
  p= 23, m= 11: b_3=     1, b_5=      36, b_7=       126, b_5/b_3=    36.0, b_7/b_5=    3.50
  p= 29, m= 14: b_3=     1, b_5=      66, b_7=       495, b_5/b_3=    66.0, b_7/b_5=    7.50
  p= 31, m= 15: b_3=     1, b_5=      78, b_7=       715, b_5/b_3=    78.0, b_7/b_5=    9.17

  Key: b_{k+2}/b_k grows with m, meaning the co-occurrence gradient
  steepens FASTER for larger cycles at larger primes.
  This explains why alpha_2+ (disjoint pairs from larger cycles)
  eventually overwhelm alpha_1 (total cycles) as p grows.
